data.title: New documentary sheds fresh light on Morecambe and Wise
data.meta_description: Next weekend, Martin narrates a two-part documentary about their career, spanning more than 40 years.
data.text:
Their greatest sketches mean more to Britain than the Crown Jewels.

Smooching with a high-kicking Angela Rippon, bashing away at the piano to the horror of André Previn, rewriting Shakespeare with Glenda Jackson as Cleopatra – Eric Morecambe and Ernie Wise are the most beloved comedians in our TV history.

Actor Martin Clunes calls them ‘the nation’s two best friends, they were having as much fun on screen as we were watching them’.

Next weekend, Martin narrates a two-part documentary about their career, spanning more than 40 years from when they were bottom-of-the-bill in wartime Blackpool to being the Queen’s favourite comics.

Though it’s packed with clips of ‘the boys’ at their best, and filled with reminiscences from family and friends, it isn’t all laughs – we also see the appalling stress success could cause, and discover the agonies of ill health Eric endured.

And there’s a major surprise right at the start. We always think of ‘little Ern’ with his ‘short, fat, hairy legs’.

But when the two first met in impresario Jack Hylton’s variety show in 1939, aged 13, before first appearing together aged 15 at the Liverpool Empire on 28 August, 1941, Ernie was the taller of the two. It was over the next few years that Eric, to his delight, grew those extra few inches.

They never forgot the first gag they did. Eric came on stage with an apple on a string, and dangled it into the orchestra pit. Ernie followed, staring in disbelief and demanding to know what Eric was playing at. ‘Fishing,’ came the reply.

‘You can’t go fishing with an apple! You need a worm,’ Ernie said. ‘It’s all right,’ Eric replied, ‘the worm’s in the apple!’

Lavishly illustrated, this documentary unearths rare photos of the duo as a teenage double act, with shots of the hoardings from the days when they performed as ‘Bartholomew and Wise’ (‘Morecambe is not my real name,’ Eric explained later to Michael Parkinson.

‘My real name’s Blackpool.’) What really brings the history to life, though, is the interviews with those who saw them honing their act decades before they reached the top.

These programmes reveal how Morecambe and Wise became the funniest men in the world through sheer hard work.

Child star Mary Naylor, now 90, remembers working with them in the 1940s. It was Ernie who won her heart – he’d been a song-and-dance performer since he was nine – and he exuded confidence. ‘He was so worldly to me,’ Mary says.

‘He was my hero.’ But she saw the leap Ernie’s career took when he found his comedy partner.

‘I don’t think Eric would have made it without Ernie, and Ernie wouldn’t have made it without Eric. It didn’t matter which one got the laughs, they were never jealous of each other.’

Even as teenagers their personalities were very different. Eric was a troublemaker – he’d sneak into the local cinema with a bag of rotten tomatoes and throw them at the screen.

‘This boy will never go anywhere,’ read his school report. Ernie was dedicated, serious and good with money. Aged 13 he was already the breadwinner in his family, and Eric’s mother Sadie realised he was just what her son needed – a good example.

After ten years touring the music halls, they got their big break on TV in 1954 with a half-hour slot on the BBC. Running Wild was supposed to make them stars. Instead, it was condemned by the critics and soon pulled off the air. One wag cruelly defined TV as ‘the box they buried Morecambe and Wise in’.

Eric, especially, was bewildered by their savage treatment. He redoubled his efforts, constantly inventing new routines and experimenting with their act as they toured Britain.

The work paid off in 1960 when they broke onto TV again in Sunday Night At The London Palladium, followed by their own show on ITV called Two Of A Kind.

This was when the duo began having star guests – a tradition that continued into The Morecambe & Wise Show years – including The Beatles. Eric tempted John Lennon into some repartee, a challenge the musician could never hope to win. When Eric asked what it was like to be so famous, Lennon teased, ‘Oh, it’s not like it was in your day. Me dad used to tell me about you,’ and he gestured with his hand at his side, as if to say, ‘I was only knee-high in those days.’ Quick as a flash, Eric copied the gesture and asked, ‘Only got a little dad, have you?’ The Beatles almost fell over laughing.

Singer Millicent Martin appeared in many of the shows, including one sketch where she was thrown over a wall and missed the mattress on the other side, almost breaking a leg. Despite the pain, she kept dancing, though the surviving footage shows how tough that must have been.

Now 82, Millicent says, ‘The hardest thing was getting through a sketch without laughing. If you laugh, you’ll ruin it.’ Welling up with tears, she adds, ‘It’s wonderful to think about those guys, it makes me very emotional.’

Flushed with success, Eric and Ernie decided to try to break America. Self-taken videos show them larking about in New York, and they appeared on the Ed Sullivan TV chat show. But Eric was wary of putting all their energy into the US. Even at the height of the ‘British Invasion’, when UK pop bands were storming the States, he feared that if they stayed away too long their own audience would forget them. Ernie disagreed, but they lived by one rule: they did nothing unless both agreed on it.

Instead, they turned their attention to films, making a series of comedy capers. The best of them, That Riviera Touch, was partly shot in the South of France and the documentary reveals dozens of behind-the-scenes stills. But their comedy style wasn’t suited to the film set, with no audiences and gags having to be repeated endlessly in the search for the perfect take.

In 1968 Morecambe and Wise switched to the BBC, where they were to have their greatest success. But the story almost ended after one series when Eric suffered a heart attack driving home after a club show.

Pulling over in his sports car, a Jensen Interceptor, he asked a passer-by to take him to hospital. The way Eric later told the story, the man said, ‘I’m in the Territorial Army, I’ve only driven a tank before!’ then put his foot down.

Eric said he felt too ill to be scared. The documentary not only tracks down the man who saved Eric’s life (Walter Butterworth, now in his 70s) but reunites him with the Jensen, which is still in the Morecambe family.

The heart attack didn’t slow Eric down. He threw himself back into the show, rehearsing to exhaustion and fretting about gags even when on holiday. Son Gary recalls how, at their villa in Portugal, he returned from a dip to find his father and sister working on a silly singing routine that would later become a stand-out sketch with Tom Jones.

Many of their best skits were inspired by Ernie’s love of song-and-dance, including perhaps the most celebrated – their recreation of the puddle-splashing from Singin’ In The Rain.

‘Ernie had that spirit about him,’ says actress Anita Harris, a regular guest. ‘He wanted to be Gene Kelly on Broadway. Ernie could really dance, and dancing with both of them just made you so happy.’

Another co-star, actress Ann Hamilton, recalls how the Christmas specials became compulsory viewing. It’s said even the Queen and her family tuned in to enjoy them. But the pressure continued to take a toll on Eric’s health.

In the late 1970s, after returning to ITV, he suffered another heart attack and vowed to slow down. He took up fishing and bird-watching, and his children noticed that for the first time he was not continually striving to win laughs at home.

Yet neither man could face retiring, having been imbued with that Northern work ethic that makes it impossible to slow down before your 60s.

Eric never made 60. He died aged 58 after coming off stage from a charity performance in Tewkesbury in 1984. Ernie soldiered on without him until his own death 15 years later, but Wise without Morecambe was like fish without chips. As Eric’s wife Joan fondly says, ‘They loved each other like brothers. It was a relationship made in heaven.’

Morecambe & Wise Forever, next Saturday and Easter Sunday, 9pm, ITV3.
